    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-10-30T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-10-30T17:00:00-05:00" n="889"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d889">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860f.00/10–3145: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Czechoslovakia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]<note n="36" xml:id="d889fn1">For remaining
                            portions of this telegram, see <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref
                                target="#pg_503">p. 503</ref>, and <ref target="frus1945v02#pg_1304"
                                >vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 1304</ref>.</note>
                    </seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Praha</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-10-31T00:00:00+02:00"
                            >October 31, 1945—midnight.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 3—1:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>509.…</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p>The President<note n="37" xml:id="d889fn2">Eduard Beneš, Czechoslovak
                        President.</note> expressed concern at the manner in which the Allies
                    continued to ignore the Czechoslovakian proposal for an exchange of minorities
                    between Hungary and Slovakia, remarking that until the minority problems in
                    Central Europe have been disposed of there could be neither stability nor
                    permanent peace. He observed that in his opinion sufficient importance was not
                    being attached by the Allies to the imperative need for solving once and for all
                    the <pb facs="0952" n="940" xml:id="pg_940"/> minority problems in and around
                    Czechoslovakia which have been the cause of so many wars for several
                        centuries.<note n="38" xml:id="d889fn3">Telegram 453, October 12, from
                        Praha, reported that during a visit to Slovakia, President Beneš bad
                        declared that Czechoslovakia must insist upon the exchange of minorities
                        between Hungary and Czechoslovakia and that at least 400,000 Magyars would
                        have to leave Czechoslovakia (840.4016/10–1245).</note>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
